          <h3>What is Visual Cryptography?</h3>
          <p>
            <b>Visual cryptography</b> is a cryptographic technique which allows <i>visual information</i> (pictures,
            text, etc.) to be encrypted in such a way that the decrypted information appears as a <b>visual image</b>.
            In 1994 Moni Naor and Adi Shamir demonstrated a <i>visual secret sharing scheme</i>, where an image was broken up into n shares so that only
            someone with all n shares could decrypt the image, while <b>any n âˆ’ 1 shares revealed no information</b>
            about the original image. Each share was printed on a separate transparency, and decryption was performed by <b>overlaying</b> the shares.
            When all n shares were overlaid, the original image did appear. There are several generalizations of the basic scheme
            including k-out-of-n visual cryptography. Using a similar idea, transparencies can be used to implement a <b>one-time pad</b>
            encryption, where one transparency is a shared random pad, and another transparency acts as the ciphertext.
          </p>
          <h3>About VCrypture</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="https://github.com/UniCT-WebDevelopment/VCrypture">VCrypture</a> is an open source online service that allows you to encrypt your <b>secret images</b> safely and send
            the result via email directly to your recipient (or just back to you). We offer four visual cryptographic algorithms: <a href="/naorshamir">Naor Shamir</a> (binary mode),
            <a href="/taghaddoslatif">Taghaddos Latif</a> (grayscale mode), <a href="/dhimankasana">Dhiman Kasana</a> EVCT(N, N) and <a href="/dhimankasana">Dhiman Kasana</a> EVCT(K, N) (both RGB mode).
          </p>
